# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uno-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The principal designers of the C# programming language were Anders Hejlsberg, Scott Wiltamuth, and Peter Golde from Microsoft.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] It was first widely distributed in July 2000 and was later approved as an international standard by Ecma (ECMA-334) in 2002 and ISO/IEC (ISO/IEC 23270 and 20619) in 2003.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft introduced C# along with .NET Framework and Microsoft Visual Studio, both of which are, technically speaking, closed-source.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] At the time, Microsoft had no open-source products.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Four years later, in 2004, a free and open-source project called Mono began, providing a cross-platform compiler and runtime environment for the C# programming language.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft released Visual Studio Code (code editor), Roslyn (compiler), and the unified .NET platform (software framework), all of which support C# and are free, open-source, and cross-platform.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono also joined Microsoft, but was not merged into .NET.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] As of November 2025, the most recent stable version of the language is C# 14.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] During the development of the .NET Framework, the class libraries were originally written using a managed code compiler system named *Simple Managed C* (SMC).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In January 1999, Anders Hejlsberg formed a team to build a new language at the time called COOL, which stood for "C-like Object Oriented Language".
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft had considered keeping the name "COOL(C-like Object Oriented Language)" as the final name of the language, but chose not to do so for trademark reasons.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] By the time the .NET project was publicly announced at the July 2000 Professional Developers Conference, the language had been renamed C#, and the class libraries and ASP.NET runtime were ported to C#.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Hejlsberg was C#'s principal designer and lead architect at Microsoft, and had been previously involved with the design of Turbo Pascal, Embarcadero Delphi (formerly CodeGear Delphi, Inprise Delphi and Borland Delphi), and Visual J++.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In interviews and technical papers, he has stated that flaws in most major programming languages (e.g.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C++, Java, Delphi, and Smalltalk) drove the fundamentals of the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which, in turn, drove the design of the C# language.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2000, Hejlsberg said that C# is "not a Java clone" and is "much closer to C++" in its design.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Since the release of C# 2.0 in November 2005, the C# and Java languages have evolved on increasingly divergent trajectories, becoming two quite different languages.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] One of the first major departures came with the addition of generics to both languages, with vastly different implementations.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# uses reification to provide "first-class" generic objects that can be used like any other class, with code generation performed at class-load time.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has also added several major features to accommodate functional-style programming, culminating in the LINQ extensions released with C# 3.0 and its supporting framework of lambda expressions, extension methods, and anonymous types.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] These features enable C# programmers to use functional programming techniques, such as closures, when it is advantageous to their application.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# used to have a mascot called Andy (named after Anders Hejlsberg).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# was originally submitted to the ISO/IEC JTC 1 subcommittee SC 22 for review, under ISO/IEC 23270:2003, was withdrawn and was then approved under ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The 23270:2006 is withdrawn under 23270:2018 and approved with this version.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft first used the name C# in 1988 for a variant of the C language designed for incremental compilation.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] That project was not completed, and the name was later reused.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The name "C sharp" was inspired by the musical notation whereby a sharp symbol indicates that the written note should be made a semitone higher in pitch.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This is similar to the language name of C++, where "++" indicates that a variable should be incremented by 1 after being evaluated.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The sharp symbol also resembles a ligature of four "+" symbols (in a two-by-two grid), further implying that the language is an increment of C++.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to technical limits of display (standard fonts, browsers, etc.), and most keyboard layouts lacking a sharp symbol (U+266F ♯ MUSIC SHARP SIGN (&sharp;)), the number sign (U+0023 # NUMBER SIGN (&num;)) was chosen to approximate the sharp symbol in the written name of the programming language.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This convention is reflected in the ECMA-334 C# Language Specification.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The "sharp" suffix has been used by a number of other Microsoft .NET compatible/compliant languages that are variants of existing languages, including J# (a .NET language also designed by Microsoft that is derived from Java 1.1), A# (from Ada), and the functional programming language F#.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The original implementation of Eiffel for .NET was called Eiffel#, a name retired since the full Eiffel language is now supported.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The suffix has also been used for libraries, such as Gtk# (a .NET wrapper for GTK and other GNOME libraries) and Cocoa# (a wrapper for Cocoa).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Development of the text for standards (beginning with C# 6) is done on GitHub.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# 7 was submitted to Ecma and approved in December 2023.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] As of January 2024, the standard for C# 8 is currently under development, referencing the approved language proposals.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] By design, C# is the programming language that most directly reflects the underlying Common Language Infrastructure (CLI).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of its intrinsic types correspond to value-types implemented by the CLI framework.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the language specification does not state the code generation requirements of the compiler: that is, it does not state that a C# compiler must target a Common Language Runtime (CLR), or generate Common Intermediate Language (CIL), or generate any other specific format.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Some C# compilers can also generate machine code like traditional compilers of Objective-C, C, C++, Assembly and Fortran.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports strongly, implicitly typed variable declarations with the keyword `var`, and implicitly typed arrays with the keyword `new[]` followed by a collection initializer.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to their special handling of the equality operator and their immutability, strings will nevertheless behave as if they were values, for all practical purposes.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The programmer can even use them as case labels.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Where necessary, value types will be boxed automatically.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports a strict Boolean data type, `bool`.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Statements that take conditions, such as `while` and `if`, require an expression of a type that evaluates to the `true` boolean value.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] While C++ also has a Boolean type, it can be freely converted to and from integers, and expressions such as `if (a)` require only that `a` is convertible to bool, allowing `a` to be an int, or a pointer.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# disallows this "integer meaning true or false" approach, on the grounds that forcing programmers to use expressions that return exactly `bool` can prevent certain types of programming mistakes such as `if (a = b)` (use of assignment `=` instead of equality `==`).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The only implicit conversions by default are those that are considered safe, such as widening of integers.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This is enforced at compile-time, during Just-in-time compilation, and, in some cases, at runtime.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] No implicit conversions occur between Booleans and integers, nor between enumeration members and integers (except for literal 0, which can be implicitly converted to any enumerated type).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Any user-defined conversion must be explicitly marked as explicit or implicit, unlike C++ copy constructors and conversion operators, which are both implicit by default.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has explicit support for covariance and contravariance in generic types, unlike C++ which has some degree of support for contravariance simply through the semantics of return types on virtual methods.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Enumeration members are placed in their own scope.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language does not allow for global variables or functions.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] All methods and members must be declared within classes.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Static members of public classes can substitute for global variables and functions.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Local variables cannot shadow variables of the enclosing block, unlike C and C++, but may shadow type-level names.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] A *method* in C# is a member of a class that can be invoked as a function, rather than the mere value-holding capability of a *field*, i.e., class or instance variable.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Different from most other languages, call-by-reference parameters have to be marked both at the function definition and at the calling site, and the programmer can choose between `ref` and `out`, the latter allowing handing over an uninitialized variable which will have a definite value on return.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Additionally, the programmer can specify a variable-sized argument list by applying the `params` keyword to the last parameter.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Certain specific kinds of methods, such as those that simply get or set a field's value by returning or assigning it, do not require an explicitly stated full signature, but in the general case, the definition of a class includes the full signature declaration of its methods.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Like C++, and unlike Java, C# programmers must use the scope modifier keyword `virtual` to allow methods to be overridden by subclasses.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, the programmer must explicitly specify the keyword `override` when doing so.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This is supposed to avoid confusion between overriding and newly overloading a function, i.e., hiding the former implementation.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] To do the latter, the programmer has to specify the `new` keyword.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The keyword `sealed` can be used to disallow further overrides for individual methods or whole classes.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The type `dynamic` allows for run-time method binding, allowing for JavaScript-like method calls and run-time object composition.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has support for strongly-typed function pointers via the keyword `delegate`.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Like the Qt framework's pseudo-C++ *signal* and *slot*, C# has semantics specifically surrounding publish-subscribe style events, though C# uses delegates to do so.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike fields, `event` variables can be part of an interface, because they technically consist of two default functions to add and remove to-be-called delegates.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# offers Java-like `synchronized` method calls, via the attribute `[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.Synchronized)]`, and has support for mutually-exclusive locks via the keyword `lock`.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The properties can be simple accessor functions with a backing field, or implement arbitrary getter and setter functions.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] A property is read-only if there's no setter.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Like with fields, there can be class and instance properties.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The underlying methods can be `virtual` or `abstract` like any other method.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Since C# 3.0 the syntactic sugar of auto-implemented properties is available, where the accessor (getter) and mutator (setter) encapsulate operations on a single field of a class.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] A C# `namespace` provides the same level of code isolation as a Java `package` or a C++ `namespace`, with rules and features very similar to a `package`.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Namespaces can be imported with the "using" syntax.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In C#, memory address pointers can only be used within blocks specifically marked as *unsafe*, and programs with unsafe code need appropriate permissions to run.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Most object access is done through safe object references, which always either point to a "live" object or have the well-defined null value; it is impossible to obtain a reference to a "dead" object (one that has been garbage collected), or to an arbitrary block of memory.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] An unsafe pointer can point to an instance of an unmanaged value type that does not contain any references to objects subject to garbage collections such as class instances, arrays or strings.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that is not marked as unsafe can still store and manipulate pointers through the `System.IntPtr` type, but it cannot dereference them.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Managed memory cannot be explicitly freed; instead, it is automatically garbage collected.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Garbage collection addresses the problem of memory leaks by freeing the programmer of responsibility for releasing memory that is no longer needed in most cases.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that retains references to objects longer than is required can still experience higher memory usage than necessary, however once the final reference to an object is released the memory is available for garbage collection.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] A range of standard exceptions are available to programmers.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Methods in standard libraries regularly throw system exceptions in some circumstances and the range of exceptions thrown is normally documented.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Custom exception classes can be defined for classes allowing handling to be put in place for particular circumstances as needed.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This is usually called a "try-catch" code block, because of the "try" and "catch" functions being used and accessible on all C# versions.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] If inspecting the error details is not required, the `(Exception ex)` parameter can be omitted as well.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Also, there can be several "catch" parts handling different kinds of exceptions.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Checked exceptions are not present in C# (in contrast to Java).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This has been a conscious decision based on the issues of scalability and version management.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, C# does not support multiple inheritance, although a class can implement any number of "interfaces" (fully abstract classes).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This was a design decision by the language's lead architect to avoid complications and to simplify architectural requirements throughout CLI.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] When implementing multiple interfaces that contain a method with the same name and taking parameters of the same types in the same order, i.e., the same signature, similar to Java, C# allows both a single method to cover all interfaces and, if necessary, specific methods for each interface.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# also offers function overloading (a.k.a. ad-hoc-polymorphism), i.e., methods with the same name, but distinguishable signatures.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike Java, C# additionally supports operator overloading.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Since version 2.0, C# offers parametric polymorphism, i.e., classes with arbitrary or constrained type parameters, e.g., `List<T>`, a variable-sized array which only can contain elements of type `T`.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] There are certain kinds of constraints the programmer can specify for the type parameters: Has to be type X (or one derived from it), has to implement a certain interface, has to be a reference type, has to be a value type, has to implement a public parameterless constructor.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of them can be combined, and any number of interfaces can be specified.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has the ability to utilize LINQ through the .NET Framework.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] A developer can query a variety of data sources, provided the `IEnumerable<T>` interface is implemented on the object.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This includes XML documents, an ADO.NET dataset, and SQL databases.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Using LINQ in C# brings advantages like IntelliSense support, strong filtering capabilities, type safety with compile error checking ability, and consistency for querying data over a variety of sources.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] There are several different language structures that can be utilized with C# and LINQ and they are query expressions, lambda expressions, anonymous types, implicitly typed variables, extension methods, and object initializers.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] LINQ has two syntaxes: query syntax and method syntax.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the compiler always converts the query syntax to method syntax at compile time.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This unified type system is called Common Type System (CTS).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] A unified type system implies that all types, including primitives such as integers, are subclasses of the `System.Object` class.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, every type inherits a `ToString()` method.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Instances of value types neither have referential identity nor referential comparison semantics.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Equality and inequality comparisons for value types compare the actual data values within the instances, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Value types are derived from `System.ValueType`, always have a default value, and can always be created and copied.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Other examples are `enum` (enumerations) and `struct` (user defined structures).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In contrast, reference types have the notion of referential identity, meaning that each instance of a reference type is inherently distinct from every other instance, even if the data within both instances is the same.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This is reflected in default equality and inequality comparisons for reference types, which test for referential rather than structural equality, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded (such as the case for `System.String`).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Some operations are not always possible, such as creating an instance of a reference type, copying an existing instance, or performing a value comparison on two existing instances.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Nevertheless, specific reference types can provide such services by exposing a public constructor or implementing a corresponding interface (such as `ICloneable` or `IComparable`).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Examples of reference types are `object` (the ultimate base class for all other C# classes), `System.String` (a string of Unicode characters), and `System.Array` (a base class for all C# arrays).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Both type categories are extensible with user-defined types.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# specification details a minimum set of types and class libraries that the compiler expects to have available.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In practice, C# is most often used with some implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI), which is standardized as ECMA-335 *Common Language Infrastructure (CLI)*.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In addition to the standard CLI specifications, there are many commercial and community class libraries that build on top of the .NET framework libraries to provide additional functionality.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# can make calls to any library included in the List of .NET libraries and frameworks.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The line above imports all types in the `System` namespace.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, the `Console` class used later in the source code is defined in the `System` namespace, meaning it can be used without supplying the full name of the type (which includes the namespace).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This line is a comment; it describes and documents the code for the programmer(s).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Above is a class definition for the `Program` class.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Everything that follows between the pair of braces describes that class.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The curly brackets demarcate the boundaries of a code block.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In this first instance, they are marking the start and end of the `Program` class.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This declares the class member method where the program begins execution.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The .NET runtime calls the `Main` method.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike in Java, the `Main` method does not need the `public` keyword, which tells the compiler that the method can be called from anywhere by any class.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Writing `static void Main(string[] args)` is equivalent to writing `private static void Main(string[] args)`.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The static keyword makes the method accessible without an instance of `Program`.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Each console application's `Main` entry point must be declared `static` otherwise the program would require an instance of `Program`, but any instance would require a program.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] To avoid that irresolvable circular dependency, C# compilers processing console applications (like that above) report an error if there is no `static Main` method.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The `void` keyword declares that `Main` has no return value.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] `Console` is a static class in the `System` namespace.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] It provides an interface to the standard input/output, and error streams for console applications.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The program calls the `Console` method `WriteLine`, which displays on the console a line with the argument, the string `"Hello, World!"`.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] With .NET 2.0 and C# 2.0, the community got more flexible collections than those in .NET 1.x.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In the absence of generics, developers had to use collections such as ArrayList to store elements as objects of unspecified kind, which incurred performance overhead when boxing/unboxing/type-checking the contained items.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Generics introduced a massive new feature in .NET that allowed developers to create type-safe data structures.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] This shift is particularly important in the context of converting legacy systems, where updating to generics can significantly enhance performance and maintainability by replacing outdated data structures with more efficient, type-safe alternatives.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In August 2001, Microsoft, Hewlett-Packard and Intel co-sponsored the submission of specifications for C# as well as the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) to the standards organization Ecma International.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In December 2001, ECMA released ECMA-334 *C# Language Specification*.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] C# became an ISO/IEC standard in 2003 (ISO/IEC 23270:2003 - *Information technology — Programming languages — C#*).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] ECMA had previously adopted equivalent specifications as the 2nd edition of C#, in December 2002.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In June 2005, ECMA approved edition 3 of the C# specification, and updated ECMA-334.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Additions included partial classes, anonymous methods, nullable types, and generics (somewhat similar to C++ templates).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2005, ECMA submitted to ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22, via the latter's Fast-Track process, the standards and related TRs.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language definition and the CLI are standardized under ISO/IEC and Ecma standards that provide reasonable and non-discriminatory licensing protection from patent claims.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft initially agreed not to sue open-source developers for violating patents in non-profit projects for the part of the framework that is covered by the Open Specification Promise.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has also agreed not to enforce patents relating to Novell products against Novell's paying customers with the exception of a list of products that do not explicitly mention C#, .NET or Novell's implementation of .NET (The Mono Project).
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] However, Novell maintained that Mono does not infringe any Microsoft patents.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft also made a specific agreement not to enforce patent rights related to the Moonlight browser plugin, which depends on Mono, provided it is obtained through Novell.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft began developing free, open-source, and cross-platform tooling for C#, namely Visual Studio Code, .NET Core, and Roslyn.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono joined Microsoft as a project of Xamarin, a Microsoft subsidiary.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has developed open-source reference C# compilers and tools.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The first compiler, Roslyn, compiles into intermediate language (IL), and the second one, RyuJIT, is a JIT (just-in-time) compiler, which is dynamic and does on-the-fly optimization and compiles the IL into native code for the front-end of the CPU.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] RyuJIT is open source and written in C++.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Roslyn is entirely written in managed code (C#), has been opened up and functionality surfaced as APIs.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] It is thus enabling developers to create refactoring and diagnostics tools.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] Two branches of official implementation are .NET Framework (closed-source, Windows-only) and .NET Core (open-source, cross-platform); they eventually converged into one open-source implementation: .NET 5.0.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] At .NET Framework 4.6, a new JIT compiler replaced the former.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The Unity game engine uses C# as its primary scripting language.
[src:uno-platform/c-sharp-programming-language] The Godot game engine has implemented an optional C# module due to a donation of $24,000 from Microsoft.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:uno-platform/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:uno-platform/skia-graphics-engine] The **Skia Graphics Engine** or **Skia** is an open-source 2D graphics library written in C++.
[src:uno-platform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia abstracts away platform-specific graphics APIs (which differ from one to another).
[src:uno-platform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia Inc. originally developed the library; Google acquired it in 2005, and then released the software as open source licensed under the New BSD free software license in 2008.
[src:uno-platform/skia-graphics-engine] In order to stay multi-platform, Skia supports several (platform-dependent) back-ends.
[src:uno-platform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia is most similar in purpose to Cairo or Pathfinder (meaning that it focuses on drawing) rather than to other more elaborate APIs like that of Qt that provide their own widgets and UI description language etc.
[src:uno-platform/skia-graphics-engine] The library is used as of 2023 in Google Chrome, ChromeOS, ChromiumOS, Mozilla Firefox, Mozilla Thunderbird, Android, Firefox OS, Flutter, Ladybird, Avalonia (from Alpha 4), LibreOffice (from version 7.0) and RAD Studio(since version 12.0).
[src:uno-platform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia is a romanisation of the word 'shadow' in Greek (Σκιά).
[src:uno-platform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia Inc, developers of the Skia Graphics Engine, was founded in 2004 by Mike Reed and Cary Clark in Chapel Hill North Carolina, before being acquired by Google in 2005.
[src:uno-platform/uno-platform] Applications can be built by using the tools in Visual Studio on Windows, including XAML and C#, and run on iOS, macOS, Android, Windows or in WebAssembly in a web browser.
[src:uno-platform/uno-platform] A plug in for Microsoft Visual Studio is available from Microsoft's Visual Studio Marketplace, VS Code Marketplace, or JetBrains Rider Marketplace.
[src:uno-platform/uno-platform] In addition to traditional IDEs, Uno Platform also offers an MCP server compatible with CLI environments and AI agents such as GitHub Copilot CLI, OpenAI Codex, Google Antigravity, and Cursor.
[src:uno-platform/uno-platform] The community surrounding Uno Platform open source project comes together at its annual conference UnoConf.
[src:uno-platform/uno-platform] Uno Platform is an open-source project sustained by a support model like Red Hat’s and via revenue from its commercial product, Uno Platform Studio, for which it raised a seed round.
[src:uno-platform/uno-platform] Microsoft and Uno Platform announced official collaboration on maintaining .NET for iOS and .NET for Android GitHub repositories, as well as co-maintenance of SkiaSharp repository.
[src:uno-platform/uno-platform] Microsoft lists Uno Platform as one of the alternatives to its own development stack.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:uno-platform/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
[src:uno-platform/winui] WinUI is one of the multiple UI frameworks provided built-in for the Windows Runtime; the others being HTML5 (e.g., via WinJS) and DirectX.
[src:uno-platform/winui] WinUI 2 is an extension library for UWP XAML containing controls and styling that match the Windows 11 design language.
[src:uno-platform/winui] It is shipped through NuGet and is distinct from the UWP XAML framework, which provides the actual rendering engine; though, they may be treated as synonyms.
[src:uno-platform/winui] WinUI 3 decouples WinRT XAML from the operating system as a separate package to be updated quickly and make new features work on older versions of Windows.
[src:uno-platform/winui] It is part of Windows App SDK (codenamed "Project Reunion"), a Microsoft effort to reconcile the Windows desktop (Win32) and the UWP low IL app model.
[src:uno-platform/winui] Up to Windows Phone 8.0 WinRT XAML was not supported and XAML applications were based on Silverlight XAML and deployed in XAP format.
[src:uno-platform/winui] In Windows Phone 8.1 WinRT XAML is available along with improved Windows Runtime support.
[src:uno-platform/winui] This convergence between platforms enable Universal apps that can target both Windows 8.1 and Windows Phone 8.1 while sharing most of the code, including user interface.
[src:uno-platform/winui] WinUI is related to Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF) and Silverlight (WPF/E)—similar XAML-based UI frameworks used for desktop applications and portable applications respectively.
[src:uno-platform/winui] WinUI uses a lot of the same names for its APIs as both of these older technologies—especially Silverlight, but its use is limited to the Windows (specifically Windows 8 and later) as with WPF.
[src:uno-platform/winui] The major difference is that WPF and Silverlight are written in C# and require using .NET languages such as C# or Visual Basic, while WinRT XAML is part of the Windows Runtime, written in C++ and available to native code, and has tools for development, with C++/CX or C++/WinRT.
